Deployment Guide
Overview
This project deploys a static HTML web application on AWS EC2, behind Nginx, with automated CI/CD via GitHub Actions,
monitoring via CloudWatch, and load testing via Apache Bench.
Architecture
Compute: EC2 t2.micro (Ubuntu 22.04), Nginx web server, region ap-south-1 (Mumbai)
Storage: S3 bucket for static asset / backup storage
Identity: IAM role devops-ec2-role attached to EC2 (least privilege — CloudWatchAgentServerPolicy +
AmazonS3ReadOnlyAccess )
Network security: Security Group restricting inbound to SSH (my IP only), HTTP, HTTPS
CI/CD: GitHub Actions — auto-deploys on every push to main
Monitoring: CloudWatch dashboard, CPU alarm, log collection
Load testing: Apache Bench ( ab ), run locally on the EC2 instance
See architecture.png for the full diagram.
Prerequisites
AWS account (Free Tier)
GitHub account
SSH key pair for EC2 ( .pem file)
Step-by-step deployment
1. GitHub repository
1. Create a new repo, e.g. devops-aws-assignment .
2. Add index.html (the app) to the repo root.
3. Create the folder .github/workflows/ and add an empty deploy.yml placeholder (filled in during Step 4 below).
2. Launch EC2 and deploy the app
1. Launch an EC2 instance: t2.micro, Ubuntu 22.04, region ap-south-1 .
2. Create/download a key pair ( .pem ) for SSH access.
3. SSH into the instance:
ssh -i "your-key.pem" ubuntu@<EC2-PUBLIC-IP>
4. Install Nginx and Apache Bench:
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y nginx apache2-utils
5. Copy index.html into /var/www/html/index.html and reload Nginx:
sudo systemctl reload nginx
6. Confirm the app loads at http://<EC2-PUBLIC-IP>/ .
3. S3 bucket
1. Create an S3 bucket, e.g. devops-assignment-backup-yourname , in ap-south-1 .
2. Keep Block all public access turned ON.
3. Upload index.html as a backup copy.
4. IAM role (least privilege)
1. IAM → Roles → Create role → Trusted entity: AWS service → Use case: EC2.
2. Attach policies: CloudWatchAgentServerPolicy , AmazonS3ReadOnlyAccess .
3. Name the role devops-ec2-role .
4. Attach it to the EC2 instance: EC2 → instance → Actions → Security → Modify IAM role.
5. Security group hardening
Inbound rules — exactly these three, nothing else:
Type Protocol Port Source Purpose
SSH TCP 22 My IP Admin access only
HTTP TCP 80 0.0.0.0/0 Public web access
HTTPS TCP 443 0.0.0.0/0 Secure web access
Outbound: left as default (all traffic, 0.0.0.0/0) so the instance can reach CloudWatch/S3/package repos.
6. CI/CD pipeline (GitHub Actions)
1. Add 3 repo secrets under Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions:
EC2_HOST — EC2 public IP
EC2_USERNAME — ubuntu
EC2_SSH_KEY — full contents of the .pem file
2. Paste the workflow into .github/workflows/deploy.yml (see pipeline-config.md ).
3. Push to main — GitHub Actions will SSH into EC2 and deploy automatically.
7. Monitoring (CloudWatch)
1. Install and start the CloudWatch agent on EC2 to collect CPU, memory, and log metrics.
2. Build a CloudWatch dashboard showing CPU utilization, network, and status checks.
3. Create an alarm CPU-High-Alert (CPU > 70% for 1 datapoint in 5 minutes).
4. Configure log collection for Nginx access logs into a CloudWatch log group.
8. Load testing
Run Apache Bench directly on the EC2 instance against localhost (see load-testing-report.md for full results):
ab -n 100 -c 10 http://localhost/
ab -n 500 -c 50 http://localhost/
ab -n 1000 -c 100 http://localhost/
